---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import TrustLine from '../components/TrustLine.astro';
import PongTribute from '../components/PongTribute.astro';

const schema = [
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "WebSite",
    "name": "1px.com",
    "url": "https://1px.com",
    "description": "The story of the single pixel that built the early web. History, technical deep-dives, and the enduring legacy of 1px.",
  },
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Organization",
    "name": "1px.com",
    "url": "https://1px.com",
    "logo": "https://1px.com/favicon.svg",
  },
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="1px.com is for sale | Premium 3-Character Domain"
  description="1px.com is for sale. A rare 3-character .com domain registered in 2002 with deep roots in web history. The single pixel that shaped the web."
  schema={schema}
>
  <section class="hero">
    <div class="hero-grid" aria-hidden="true"></div>
    <div class="hero-content">
      <h1>1px<span class="hero-tld">.com</span></h1>
      <p class="hero-subtitle">The single pixel that shaped the web</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <article>
    <p class="intro"><em>Before CSS existed, the entire visual web was held together by an invisible 1&times;1 pixel transparent GIF. Designers stretched it, duplicated it, and embedded it millions of times to build the layouts we take for granted today.</em></p>

    <p class="intro"><em><strong>1px</strong> is where that story lives. From the spacer GIF era of the late 1990s to the sub-pixel rendering challenges of modern retina displays, the single pixel remains the fundamental unit of everything we see on screen.</em></p>

    <h2>Explore the World of 1px</h2>

    <div class="content-grid">
      <a href="/spacer-gif-history/" class="content-card">
        <h3>The Spacer GIF Story</h3>
        <p>How a 43-byte transparent image became the most important file on the early web, powering table-based layouts across millions of sites.</p>
      </a>

      <a href="/1px-css-borders/" class="content-card">
        <h3>1px Borders in CSS</h3>
        <p>The retina display problem, hairline rendering techniques, and why a single pixel border is still one of the hardest things in web development.</p>
      </a>

      <a href="/px-unit-explained/" class="content-card">
        <h3>The PX Unit Explained</h3>
        <p>A CSS pixel is not a physical pixel. Dive into what PX actually means, the rem vs px debate, and every other meaning of those two letters.</p>
      </a>

      <a href="/power-of-one/" class="content-card">
        <h3>The Power of 1</h3>
        <p>Why single-character domains command premium value, how "1" leads in every sorted list, and the brands that chose to start with one.</p>
      </a>

      <a href="/about-this-domain/" class="content-card">
        <h3>About This Domain</h3>
        <p>Registered May 4, 2002. A rare 3-character .com with 24 years of history, clean WHOIS record, and perfect Lighthouse scores.</p>
      </a>

      <PongTribute />
    </div>

    <h2>Why 1px.com</h2>

    <p>Three characters. Universal recognition. A domain that speaks directly to anyone who has ever written a line of HTML or CSS. <strong>1px.com</strong> is not just short and memorable — it carries meaning. It references the foundational building block of digital visual media: the pixel.</p>

    <p>Whether as a brand for a design tool, a CSS framework, a creative agency, or a technical publication, <strong>1px.com</strong> signals precision, craft, and deep web heritage.</p>

    <aside class="article-cta">
      <p>This premium 3-character .com domain is available for purchase.</p>
      <a href="https://forsale.godaddy.com/forsale/1px.com" class="cta-button" rel="noopener">Make an Offer on 1px.com</a>
      <TrustLine />
    </aside>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
